{"text": "V (x) and A(x). In the translated reference frame the new basis is \u0303x\u27e9\u2261 x + a\u27e9, hence \u27e8 \u0303x H \u0303x\u2032\u27e9= \u27e8x \u0303H x\u2032\u27e9with\n\n\u0303H = D\u2020HD. Hence we deduce that the Hamiltonian is \u201dinvariant\u201d (keeps its form) with\n\n\u0303V (x)\n\n=\n\nV (x + a)\n\n(9.11)\n\n\u0303A(x)\n\n=\n\nA(x + a)\n\n(9.12)\n\nIn order to verify that we are not confused with the signs, let us consider the potential V (x) = \u03b4(x). If we make a\n\ntranslation with a = 7, then the basis in the new reference frame will be \u0303x\u27e9= x + 7\u27e9, and we get \u0303V (x) = \u03b4(x + 7)\n\nwhich means a delta at x = \u22127.\n\nFor completeness we cite how the Hamiltonian transform under Galilean transformation T to a moving frame whose\n\nvelocity is v0. This transformation is composed of a translation e\u2212iv0t\u02c6p and a boost eimv0\u02c6x. The following result is\n\nderived in a dedicated lecture:\n\n\u0303H\n\n=\n\nT \u2020 H T \u2212v0 \u00b7 \u02c6p\n\n=\n\nh(\u02c6x, \u02c6p; \u0303V , \u0303A)\n\n(9.13)\n\nwhere\n\n\u0303V (x)\n\n=\n\nV (x + v0t) \u2212v0 \u00b7 A(x + v0t)\n\n(9.14)\n\n\u0303A(x)\n\n=\n\nA(x + v0t)\n\n(9.15)\n\nFrom here follows the well know no-relativistic transformation \u0303E = E + v0 \u00d7 B, and \u0303B = B.\n\n48\n\n====== [9.4] The dynamical phase, electric field\n\nConsider the case where there is no hopping between sites (c0 = 0). Accordingly the Hamiltonian H = V (x) does not\n\ninclude a kinetic part, and the evolution operator is \u02c6U(t) = exp[\u2212itV (\u02c6x)]. A particle that is located in a given point\n\nin space will accumulate so called a dynamical phase:\n\n\u02c6U(t) x0\u27e9\n\n=\n\ne\u2212itV (x0) x0\u27e9\n\n(9.16)\n\nThe potential V is the \u201ddynamical phase\u201d that the particle accumulates per unit time. The V in a specific site is\n\ncalled \u201dbinding energy\u201d or \u201don site energy\u201d or \u201dpotential energy\u201d depending on the physical context. A V (x) that\n\nchanges from site to site reflects the non-homogeneity of the space, or the presence of an \u201dexternal field\u201d. To further\n\nclarify the significance of V let us consider a simple prototype example. Let us assume that V (x) = \u2212Ex.", "embedding": [-0.0024179774, 0.023833139, 0.023125814, -0.006215753, -0.005883375, 0.0018392438, 0.0112228, 0.0016460103, -0.040442817, 0.06577593, 0.031069828, 0.0044047795, 0.013759275, -0.033024874, -0.02728361, 0.002627853, -0.017542945, -0.03381009, -0.08331519, 0.024954846, 0.030036433, 0.005062583, -0.078861475, -0.04193874, -0.006936836, 0.027817937, 0.017516967, -0.010220076, 0.06342191, 0.06313108, 0.016711934, -0.005672621, 0.020330012, -0.020725599, -0.011077845, 0.027914645, -0.009117872, -0.03711647, 0.0487176, -0.027637687, 0.06902898, -0.023869539, 0.020594904, -0.0034178915, -0.060522262, -0.036907826, -0.0027556561, -0.0014927693, -0.0466224, -0.051494587, 0.019780613, 0.014135492, 0.025302485, -0.016358443, -0.0072805635, 0.005368116, -0.006996103, 0.0033264197, -0.015941305, 0.032548297, 0.032410633, -0.0043768715, 0.0021224984, -0.04206941, -0.011692651, 0.030271282, -0.018948123, 0.03044956, 0.004031469, -0.026139932, -0.014520338, 0.0028907887, 0.0018097925, 0.020397728, -0.063795865, 0.053043455, -0.010605199, -0.050332773, -0.046882, -0.008699876, -0.0022396029, -0.02160882, -0.0016053672, 0.012662372, -0.030856919, 0.010358333, -0.0116807055, -0.03735174, 0.010166424, -0.004268621, 0.020078659, 0.053071823, -0.03148705, -0.005011484, 0.018037688, 0.060544085, -0.012272113, 0.030032717, 0.048761394, 0.005561077, -0.019388385, 0.055451974, -0.03173456, 0.03588396, -0.046439685, 0.031310007, -0.008724114, 0.012602702, -0.0029921746, -0.058340453, 0.048430786, -0.0003010467, 0.01031544, 0.008965627, 0.0073017837, 0.037757657, 0.015144104, -0.011951869, -0.011108555, -0.058201943, 0.016922804, -0.01361947, 0.029094396, 0.06829342, 0.006738844, -0.0036088252, 0.0004413